    "71223008": {
      "title": "Nutrition Education for Schoolchildren Living in a Low-Income Urban Area in Spain",
      "abstract": "Abstract An investigation into the nutritional habits of the school-aged population of Bilbao showed that while most districts reflected the characteristics of so called \"affluent societies,\" there were some deprived areas in which urgent action was needed. A pilot nutrition education program was carried out in a school in one such deprived area with a high proportion of Gypsy students. The project curriculum identified objectives for the classroom, the school environment, and the home. The first stage involved 150 8 to 12 year olds. The first part of the project dealt with the training of the teachers and other school personnel. Classroom objectives were introduced into different subjects. A variety of teaching methods were used to achieve the learning objectives of changing the children's attitudes to, and improving their understanding of, nutrition. The activities included drawing, craft work, and puppet shows. The children developed food preparation skills, sampled new dishes, and learned table manners during a five-session cookery workshop. A menu plan was developed for the school lunchroom. Qualitative evaluation was carried out by means of ethnographic observational methods, which assessed acceptance of and involvement in the project, group building, and changes in eating habits and practices. After 2 years of implementation, evaluation results showed improvement in knowledge and skills. The children were willing to try a greater variety of fruit, vegetables, and pulses in the school lunchroom.There were positive changes in personal hygiene habits but poor results in dental hygiene practices. Sixty percent of the children cooked some of the suggested recipes at home."
